The '''Ligier JS21''' was a [[Formula One]] [[racing car]] manufactured and raced by [[Equipe Ligier|Ligier]] during the [[1983 Formula One season]].  Powered by a Cosworth V8 engine while the majority of teams used turbo power, the team failed to score any points.

==Development==
The JS21 was designed by [[Claude Galopin]] under the technical direction of Michel Beaujon. Henri Durand worked on the car's aerodynamics.<ref name=Statsf1/> Having used [[Talbot]] engines for the previous two seasons, the JS21 was designed to be powered by a Ford [[Cosworth DFV]].<ref name=Nye>Nye, 1985, p. 194</ref> Ligier was the first choice to be the recipient of the then-new Honda turbo engine due to team owner Guy Ligier's longstanding relationship with Honda but the team declined to use it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JYjYhKdSHyI|author=Motors TV|title=The Ligier Saga|work=YouTube|date=|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> The first three JS21 chassis were converted from the previous year's JS19, with four in total being built.<ref name=Nye>Nye, 1985, p. 194</ref>

==Racing history==
The Ligier team recruited two new drivers for the 1983 season, [[Jean-Pierre Jarier]], who had a single outing for the team back in 1977, and Brazilian novice [[Raul Boesel]]. Jarier qualified for every race with a best grid placing of 9th, at the [[1983 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grand Prix]]. His best finish was 7th in [[1983 Austrian Grand Prix|Austria]]. For most of the season, Boesel usually qualified several places behind Jarier but improved towards the season's end although he did miss qualifying for the Austrian and [[1983 Italian Grand Prix|Italian races]]. His best qualifying was 17th, in the season opening [[1983 Brazilian Grand Prix|Brazilian Grand Prix]], and he achieved his best finish of 7th the following race in the United States.<ref name=Statsf1/>

1983 was the first season in the team's history that it failed to score a single point. For the following year, team owner [[Guy Ligier]] secured the use of Renault V6 turbocharged engines.<ref name=Nye/>
